data.content:
Three things break. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — expression tree no longer compiles

A new non-expression overload (`Func<…>` instead of `Expression<Func<…>>`) now takes priority, so your hand-built expression tree won't compile. **Replace it entirely** with a simple lambda:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Call` / `Expression.Lambda` — conditionals go directly inside the lambda now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Same-name properties are uniquified.** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared one column silently; now EF appends a number to disambiguate. To keep the old (shared) column names, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use full-path column names.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to `BillingAddress_City`; now it becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> If you're starting fresh (no existing database), the new defaults are fine — just be aware that a migration will be generated to rename columns.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

All methods like `CommandReaderExecuting` gained a `string logCommandText` parameter (contains SQL with inlined constants redacted). Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the real SQL
    }
}
```

Update the same way for `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc. — they all got the same additional parameter.
